'''George David Eric Hirst''' (born 15 February 1999) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for {{English football updater|IpswichT}} club [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]. Born in England, he plays for the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].<ref>{{cite web |date=19 March 2025 |title=Ex-England striker dad backed Hirst's Scotland switch |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c7vz9vr6564o |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early life===
George Hirst is the son of former [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] striker [[David Hirst (footballer)|David Hirst]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/c4g7ddrp62ko|title=Who is George Hirst? The 'unit' Steve Clarke was scouting|date=4 March 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

===Sheffield Wednesday===
After coming through the academy, Hirst signed his first professional contract for [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] in March 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |date=30 March 2016 |title=George Hirst pens first Owls professional contract |url=http://www.swfc.co.uk/news/article/george-hirst-pens-first-owls-professional-contract-3033159.aspx |website=www.swfc.co.uk}}</ref>

He made his first team debut against [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]] on 9 August 2016, in the [[EFL Cup]] in a 2–1 defeat.<ref name="George Hirst">{{Cite web |date=17 June 2018 |title=George Hirst |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=94672&season_id=149 |website=SoccerBase}}</ref> His league debut came on 10 December 2016 against [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] in a 2–1 defeat.<ref name="George Hirst" /> In April 2018, Hirst was linked with a move to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] after rejecting a long-term contract at [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 April 2018 |title=Manchester United targeting George Hirst, suggests Sheffield Wednesday boss Jos Luhukay |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/11324323/manchester-united-targeting-george-hirst-suggests-sheffield-wednesday-boss-jos-luhukay |access-date=17 June 2018 |publisher=Sky Sports}}</ref>

===OH Leuven===
In June 2018, Hirst was signed by a second division Belgian team, [[Oud-Heverlee Leuven]], led by former Sheffield Wednesday player [[Nigel Pearson]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=23 June 2018 |title=Leicester City target George Hirst signs for sister club OH Leuven |url=https://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/leicester-city-target-george-hirst-1708563 |access-date=3 August 2018 |publisher=Leicester Mercury}}</ref>

===Leicester City===
After just one season at OH Leuven, Hirst joined [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] in the summer of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |date=5 July 2019 |title=Leicester City Sign Trio Of Youth Internationals |url=https://www.lcfc.com/news/1260931/leicester-city-sign-trio-of-youth-internationals/press-release |access-date=5 July 2019 |publisher=Leicester Mercury}}</ref> On 19 July 2020 Hirst made his debut for Leicester, coming on in the 83rd minute in a 3–0 loss to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].

====Rotherham United (loan)====
On 16 September 2020, Hirst joined [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] on a season-long loan deal.<ref>{{Cite web |date=16 September 2020 |title=SIGNING {{!}} Millers land long-term target on loan |url=https://www.themillers.co.uk/news/2020/september/signing--millers-land-long-term-target-on-loan/ |publisher=[[Rotherham United F.C.]]}}</ref>

====Portsmouth (loan)====
On 3 August 2021, Hirst joined [[EFL League One|League One]] side [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] on loan for the [[2021–22 Portsmouth F.C. season|2021–22 season]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=3 August 2021 |title=Hirst Arrives On Loan |url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2021/august/hirst-arrives-on-loan/ |website=www.portsmouthfc.co.uk}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 9 November 2021 in an [[EFL Trophy]] tie against [[Crystal Palace F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Crystal Palace U21s]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=9 November 2021 |title=Pompey 3 Crystal Palace U21 0 |publisher=portsmouthfc.co.uk |url=https://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/news/2021/november/match-report-for-portsmouth-vs-crystal-palace-u21-on-09-nov-21/ |access-date=15 November 2021}}</ref>

====Blackburn Rovers (loan)====
On 31 August 2022, Hirst joined [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] on a season-long loan, with an option to buy.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Blackburn sign Leicester striker Hirst on loan |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62743031 |access-date=2022-09-09}}</ref>

====Ipswich Town (loan)====
On 8 January 2023, Hirst joined [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] on loan for the rest of the season.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Ipswich Town: George Hirst arrives after a rollercoaster career |language=en-GB |work=East Anglian Daily Times |url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/sport/23236616.ipswich-town-george-hirst-arrives-rollercoaster-career/ |access-date=2023-01-09}}</ref>

===Ipswich Town===
On 13 July 2023, Hirst made his move to [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] permanent for a undisclosed fee, signing a four-year deal with the club.<ref>{{cite web |title=George Hirst Joins Ipswich Town |url=https://www.lcfc.com/news/3589019/george-hirst-joins-ipswich-town |publisher= LCFC |date=13 July 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Warren |first=Andy |date=12 July 2023 |title=George Hirst Returns To Town |url=https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2023/july/12/hirst-returns-to-town/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230713094126/https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2023/july/12/hirst-returns-to-town/ |archive-date=13 July 2023 |access-date=13 July 2023 |website=Ipswich Town FC |publisher=}}</ref> He scored his first ever [[EFL Championship|Championship]] goal on his second debut for the club, netting against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] on the opening day of the [[2023–24 Ipswich Town F.C. season|2023–24 season]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Warren |first=Andy |date=2023-08-07 |title=George Delighted to Open Account |url=https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2023/august/07/george-delighted-to-open-account/ |access-date=2023-08-07 |website=Ipswich Town FC |language=en}}</ref>

Whilst playing against his former club, Leicester City, on 26 December 2023, he suffered a "significant" hamstring injury which would put him out for a majority of the rest of the season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67833521|title=Ipswich's Hirst out with 'significant' injury|work=BBC Sport |date=28 December 2023 }}</ref> He returned for the final three games of the season, beginning with the 3–3 draw against [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] on 27 April, starting the match and scoring the first goal of the game. He then started on the bench in the following game against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], before starting the final game of the season, a 2–0 victory over [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] where Ipswich were promoted to the [[2024–25 Premier League|Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Warren |first=Andy |url=https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2024/may/04/ipswich-town-v-huddersfield-match-report/ |title=TOWN 2 HUDDERSFIELD 0 |publisher=Ipswich Town F.C. |date=4 May 2024 }}</ref>

He scored his first Premier League goal for Ipswich on 26 October 2024, his first game in the starting lineup, in which the ''Tractor Boys'' went on to lose 4–3 at [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]], having been two goals up in the first half.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cvgdggd7j4kt|title=Brentford 4-3 Ipswich: Clarke has afternoon to forget|last=Thomas|first=Marissa|website=BBC Sport|date=26 October 2024|access-date=29 October 2024}}</ref> On 4 July 2025, he extended his contract with the club until 2029.<ref>{{cite web |last=Warren |first=Andy |url=https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2025/july/04/george-hirst-signs-new-contract/ |title=NEW DEAL FOR HIRSTY |publisher=Ipswich Town F.C. |date=4 July 2025 }}</ref>

==International career==
Hirst was eligible to represent England as his birthplace and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] via his [[paternal]] grandfather.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/c4g7ddrp62ko|title='Powerful & intelligent' Hirst different to other Scotland strikers|last=Canavan|first=Amy|date=4 March 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

===England youth===
Hirst made his debut for the [[England national under-17 football team|England Under-17]] national team during the Algarve Cup in February 2016 – in his second game for the team he scored twice against [[Germany national youth football team|Germany]] in a 2–2 draw.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Hayes Saves Penalty and Dozzell Skippers as England U17s Draw With Germany – Ipswich Town News |url=https://www.twtd.co.uk/ipswich-town-news/29026/hayes-saves-penalty-and-dozzell-skippers-as-england-u17s-draw-with-germany |access-date=26 February 2020 |website=TWTD.co.uk}}</ref> He was subsequently called up to the squad for the [[2016 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] in Azerbaijan.<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 May 2016 |title=England Under-17s squad named for Euro Championship |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2016/may/04/euro-finals-squad-announced-040516 |access-date=9 September 2017 |publisher=The Football Association}}</ref> In the group stage Hirst scored against [[Denmark national under-17 football team|Denmark]]<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 May 2016 |title=England U17s into Euro quarter finals after win over Denmark |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2016/may/12/uefa-u17s-championship-england-denmark-azerbaijan |access-date=9 September 2017 |publisher=The Football Association}}</ref> and started the Quarter-final defeat against [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 May 2016 |title=England Under-17s miss out on semi-final after loss to Spain |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2016/may/15/spain-england-report-150516 |access-date=9 September 2017 |publisher=The Football Association}}</ref>

On 23 August 2016, Hirst was called up to the [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]]s for the first time.<ref>{{Cite web |date=23 August 2016 |title=Hirst called up for England Under-18s |url=https://www.swfc.co.uk/news/2016/august/hirst-called-up-for-england-under-18s/ |access-date=23 August 2016 |publisher=www.swfc.co.uk}}</ref> In summer 2017, Hirst represented England Under 20s at the [[2017 Toulon Tournament]], scoring a hat-trick in a game against [[Cuba national under-20 football team|Cuba]]<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 June 2017 |title=Hat-trick for George Hirst as U20s book Toulon Tournament semi-final spot |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2017/jun/01/toulon-tournament-england-u20s-7-1-cuba-match-report-george-hirst-010617 |access-date=9 September 2017 |publisher=The Football Association}}</ref> to take his 2016–17 tally to 40 goals in all competitions.<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 June 2017 |title=That's 40! Sheffield Wednesday's George Hirst on target again for England in Toulon Tournament |url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/news/thats-40-sheffield-wednesdays-george-hirst-target-again-england-toulon-tournament-444414 |access-date=16 February 2022 |publisher=Sheffield Star}}</ref> Hirst started in the final against the [[Ivory Coast national under-20 football team|Ivory Coast]] which England won on penalties<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 June 2017 |title=Spot on Young Lions hold their nerve to retain Toulon Tournament title |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2017/jun/10/england-v-ivory-coast-report-100617 |access-date=9 September 2017 |publisher=The Football Association}}</ref><ref name="2017Toulon">{{Cite news |date=10 June 2017 |title=Toulon Tournament: England 1-1 Ivory Coast (5-3 penalties) |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40236422 |access-date=14 June 2017}}</ref> and was subsequently named in the team of the tournament.<ref name="Toulon">{{Cite web |date=12 June 2017 |title=Hirst named in Team of the Tournament |url=https://www.swfc.co.uk/news/2017/june/hirst-named-in-team-of-the-tournament/ |access-date=9 September 2017 |publisher=www.swfc.co.uk}}</ref>

On 1 September 2017, Hirst scored his second hat-trick of the Summer in a victory against [[Poland national under-19 football team|Poland]], for [[England national under-19 football team|England Under-19]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 September 2017 |title=Paul Simpson's young Lions kick-off their season in style at St. George's Park |url=https://www.thefa.com/news/2017/sep/01/england-u19s-poland-report-010917 |access-date=16 February 2022 |publisher=The Football Association}}</ref> In July 2018, Hirst was included in the squad for the [[2018 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=16 July 2018 |title=England U19 boss Paul Simpson has named his squad for 2018 Euro Finals in Finland |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2018/jul/16/england-u19s-squad-named-for-euro-finals-160718 |access-date=3 August 2018 |publisher=The Football Association}}</ref>

In May 2019, Hirst was included in the [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] squad for the [[2019 Toulon Tournament]].<ref name="EnglandU10">{{Cite web |title=ENGLAND MU20S SQUAD NAMED BY PAUL SIMPSON FOR MAURICE REVELLO TOURNAMENT IN FRANCE |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2019/may/28/england-u20-squad-named-for-maurice-revello-tournament-280519 |access-date=1 June 2019 |website=TheFA.com}}</ref>

===Scotland===
On 11 March 2025, Hirst declared for Scotland through a change of association approved by [[FIFA]].<ref name="FIFA-Change">{{Cite web|url=https://knowledge.fifa.com/change-of-association-platform|title=FIFA Change of Association Platform|accessdate=11 March 2025}}</ref> He made his full international debut later that month, in a [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League|Nations League]] match against [[Greece national football team|Greece]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/sport/25025538.ipswich-town-george-hirst-makes-scotland-debut-quartet-earn-caps/ |title=Ipswich Town: George Hirst makes Scotland debut as quartet earn caps |newspaper=East Anglian Daily Times |first=Alex |last=Jones|date=20 March 2025 |accessdate=10 June 2025}}</ref> Hirst then scored his first Scotland goal on 9 June 2025, during a [[friendly match|friendly]] with [[Liechtenstein national football team|Liechtenstein]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/jun/09/liechtenstein-scotland-international-friendly-match-report |title=Hirst off mark and Adams ends drought in style as Scotland thrash Liechtenstein |newspaper=The Guardian |date=9 June 2025 |accessdate=10 June 2025}}</ref>

